@flice lstm is not pre-requisite here, I also have tried cnn model, and it also works well for only digits dicts.
But for larger dicts, such Chinese characters, about 5000+ elements, we need to design sophisticated nets.
I use lstm as the example supplied, I succeeded.

You can modify the metric function to save the predicted outputs. For example in the accuracy function:
`mx.metric.accuracy <- mx.metric.custom("accuracy", function(label, pred) {
  ypred = max.col(t(as.array(pred)), tie="first")
  return(sum((as.array(label) + 1) == ypred) / length(label))
})`

the label and predicted data are passed and you can implement the saving feature here.

@abuzn shape change every is possible in mxnet, but your case is special because the out shape of the customOp is related to the inData which is not known in the inferShape but only known in the forward pass.
I am not sure whether this is possible in mxnet.
